1
00:00:00,320 --> 00:00:05,619
When the market has a clean breakout, it often
likes to revisit that breakout point before

2
00:00:05,619 --> 00:00:08,440
continuing in the breakout direction.

3
00:00:08,440 --> 00:00:12,810
And I bet you’re actively looking for these
retests as valid opportunities.

4
00:00:12,810 --> 00:00:14,880
There’s nothing new here.

5
00:00:14,880 --> 00:00:16,540
But here’s the thing.

6
00:00:16,540 --> 00:00:22,050
The strategies in most trading books don't
really match what big smart money traders

7
00:00:22,050 --> 00:00:23,289
are actually doing.

8
00:00:23,289 --> 00:00:29,430
There’s a big difference between where smart
money sees a technical support versus our

9
00:00:29,430 --> 00:00:32,720
retail support levels.

10
00:00:32,720 --> 00:00:38,680
Breakout retests happen because the big boys
are still trying to enter or exit positions.

11
00:00:38,680 --> 00:00:45,230
When the market breaks past certain levels,
it attracts a bunch of new buyers and sellers.

12
00:00:45,230 --> 00:00:50,950
After breaking a high or low, the price will
often swing back to where it started.

13
00:00:50,950 --> 00:00:57,150
This is so smart money can fill more orders
from traders betting on the breakout.

14
00:00:57,150 --> 00:01:02,880
Before it happens, many traders place pending
orders, waiting to join the move.

15
00:01:02,880 --> 00:01:07,530
Once the breakout goes through, it triggers
all those orders.

16
00:01:07,530 --> 00:01:13,740
And then some smart money traders will start
taking profits since they got in early before

17
00:01:13,740 --> 00:01:16,320
the move was obvious to us.

18
00:01:16,320 --> 00:01:22,149
Their profit-taking causes the market to retrace
back to the original breakout point.

19
00:01:22,149 --> 00:01:28,000
It gives late traders a second chance to hop
in, while also letting smart money lock in

20
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:29,710
their gains.

21
00:01:29,710 --> 00:01:35,049
That's why breakout retests tend to provide
trading opportunities - big players are still

22
00:01:35,049 --> 00:01:36,869
moving in and out!

23
00:01:36,869 --> 00:01:42,560
Also, there’s another reason why breakouts
tend to retrace after a big move.

24
00:01:42,560 --> 00:01:47,759
It's because many traders start closing their
positions too early!

25
00:01:47,759 --> 00:01:53,550
When the price breaks past a level, breakout
traders will jump in, hoping the price keeps

26
00:01:53,550 --> 00:01:54,550
running.

27
00:01:54,550 --> 00:02:01,099
But as it comes back down towards where they
got in, their profits start getting smaller

28
00:02:01,099 --> 00:02:02,840
and smaller.

29
00:02:02,840 --> 00:02:06,340
Most people probably panic seeing their gains
decrease.

30
00:02:06,340 --> 00:02:11,000
So they bail while there's still a little
profit left.

31
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:17,540
The closer it trades to the breakout point,
more and more traders will close out of fear.

32
00:02:17,540 --> 00:02:23,000
This creates a pile of sell orders that smart
money can use to their advantage.

33
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:29,560
Big institutions enter by picking off the
orders of stopped out retail traders.

34
00:02:29,560 --> 00:02:36,290
Then once they build their positions, the
retrace will end and the move continues.

35
00:02:36,290 --> 00:02:40,480
It helps to see retests differently than just
a retracement.

36
00:02:40,480 --> 00:02:45,989
They're actually the market's way of resetting
itself after a big move.

37
00:02:45,989 --> 00:02:52,620
By "resetting", I mean it gets rid of weak
positions held by traders who can't handle

38
00:02:52,620 --> 00:02:54,340
the volatility.

39
00:02:54,340 --> 00:03:01,120
These are usually retailers like us who bail
too early before the move really takes off.

40
00:03:01,120 --> 00:03:08,040
Either we panic seeing our profits erode,
or trade really short timeframes just looking

41
00:03:08,040 --> 00:03:09,920
for tiny gains.

42
00:03:09,920 --> 00:03:16,790
Either way, when a retest happens, it tends
to shake these weak hands out before the next

43
00:03:16,790 --> 00:03:18,459
wave up.

44
00:03:18,459 --> 00:03:23,090
After the reset, there's less resistance at
that level.

45
00:03:23,090 --> 00:03:30,150
And now smart money have a chance to buy more
at cheap prices, from the stopped out traders.

46
00:03:30,150 --> 00:03:35,849
At the retest point, the big boys are free
to drive the move further without as much

47
00:03:35,849 --> 00:03:38,370
selling pressure.

48
00:03:38,370 --> 00:03:44,310
When a drop happens, you can see the zone
where a ton of traders had sell orders set

49
00:03:44,310 --> 00:03:46,170
beforehand.

50
00:03:46,170 --> 00:03:51,510
Once the downward breakout goes through, the
market will usually keep falling for a bit

51
00:03:51,510 --> 00:03:54,450
as momentum carries it lower.

52
00:03:54,450 --> 00:04:00,040
And then the big money players start locking
in profits on their short trades.

53
00:04:00,040 --> 00:04:07,100
As they close positions, it pushes the price
back up towards the original break point.

54
00:04:07,100 --> 00:04:13,590
As price moves higher, trapped sellers are
bound to bail and exit, scared of losing more

55
00:04:13,590 --> 00:04:18,610
money, flooding the market with buy orders,
their stops.

56
00:04:18,610 --> 00:04:25,160
Then smart money swoops in to fill all these
reversing orders on the way back up.

57
00:04:25,160 --> 00:04:30,800
If you think about it, no wonder retests tend
to be so strong - they're capitalizing on

58
00:04:30,800 --> 00:04:35,020
multiple trader types repositioning themselves!

59
00:04:35,020 --> 00:04:39,740
This is how the big players manipulate these
patterns.

60
00:04:39,740 --> 00:04:44,729
Another reason why so many people struggle
trading breakout retests – it’s because

61
00:04:44,729 --> 00:04:48,610
the way they're marking these levels is all
wrong!

62
00:04:48,610 --> 00:04:52,780
Most people just draw a single line where
the breakout happened.

63
00:04:52,780 --> 00:04:58,600
But with how messy charts can be, that forces
you to guess exactly which point price will

64
00:04:58,600 --> 00:05:01,250
revisit, which is basically impossible.

65
00:05:01,250 --> 00:05:05,470
And no wonder so many retest trades end up
as losses.

66
00:05:05,470 --> 00:05:11,190
I said it many times before, start using areas
instead of lines and it will made a huge difference.

67
00:05:11,190 --> 00:05:17,600
If there's a cluster of highs or lows in the
breakout zone, I'll highlight the whole region

68
00:05:17,600 --> 00:05:20,550
rather than a specific price.

69
00:05:20,550 --> 00:05:28,210
That way, no matter where it comes back to
within that area, my analysis still applies.

70
00:05:28,210 --> 00:05:33,800
This takes the guessing game out of figuring
out the exact retest level.

71
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:40,949
As long as price re-entries your highlighted
region, you can take the trade.

72
00:05:40,949 --> 00:05:45,900
Making this simple adjustment has made trading
breakouts much more reliable.

73
00:05:45,900 --> 00:05:51,830
In this chart, you can see there were two
highs close together that triggered breakout

74
00:05:51,830 --> 00:05:53,210
buys.

75
00:05:53,210 --> 00:05:59,860
In the moment, you wouldn't know which exact
high the price might drop back to test.

76
00:05:59,860 --> 00:06:05,389
That's why it's way better to highlight the
whole zone between the highs instead of just

77
00:06:05,389 --> 00:06:06,560
drawing a line.

78
00:06:06,560 --> 00:06:13,419
That way, whether it hits the first or second
high on a retest, your area still covers it.

79
00:06:13,419 --> 00:06:20,460
By outlining a broad region instead of trying
to pinpoint one level, you take out lots of

80
00:06:20,460 --> 00:06:22,139
guesswork.

81
00:06:22,139 --> 00:06:27,560
Marking breakdowns and breakouts as trading
ranges just makes so much more sense than

82
00:06:27,560 --> 00:06:29,120
rigid lines.

83
00:06:29,120 --> 00:06:33,430
It builds in more wiggle room for when the
price retraces.

84
00:06:33,430 --> 00:06:39,210
Now very important: when trading these breakout
retests is all about reading each market’s

85
00:06:39,210 --> 00:06:40,599
individual tendencies.

86
00:06:40,599 --> 00:06:45,729
What works on one market may fail totally
for another one.

87
00:06:45,729 --> 00:06:51,220
There's no formula that instantly makes you
a pro - it comes down to watching price action

88
00:06:51,220 --> 00:06:55,960
over time so you get a feel for how each one
behaves.

89
00:06:55,960 --> 00:07:01,350
The more markers and consolidations you witness,
the better calls you'll make.

90
00:07:01,350 --> 00:07:07,040
Also, for a breakout to be legit, look for
two signs.

91
00:07:07,040 --> 00:07:13,479
First there needs to be a noticeable gap in
the close price through the level, not just

92
00:07:13,479 --> 00:07:14,479
a wick.

93
00:07:14,479 --> 00:07:15,539
That shows commitment.

94
00:07:15,539 --> 00:07:18,270
Second, check volume.

95
00:07:18,270 --> 00:07:24,349
If it spikes on the candle that clears the
zone, that validates buyers/sellers are stepping

96
00:07:24,349 --> 00:07:25,349
up.

97
00:07:25,349 --> 00:07:29,020
Low volume breaks are suspect.

98
00:07:29,020 --> 00:07:32,889
When looking for valid breakouts, volume is
key.

99
00:07:32,889 --> 00:07:38,110
For the move to have strength, you need to
see rising volume on the initial push through

100
00:07:38,110 --> 00:07:39,419
resistance.

101
00:07:39,419 --> 00:07:43,180
This shows real buying pressure forcing the
break.

102
00:07:43,180 --> 00:07:48,500
But then volume is just as important on the
retracement - it should be lower than the

103
00:07:48,500 --> 00:07:49,760
breakout.

104
00:07:49,760 --> 00:07:55,949
If volume stays high as it pulls back, that
tells you sellers are still in control and

105
00:07:55,949 --> 00:07:58,090
it may just be a trap.

106
00:07:58,090 --> 00:08:02,199
You want evidence of buying demand strengthening
again.

107
00:08:02,199 --> 00:08:07,440
Ideally at the retest zone, volume will start
to pick up too.

108
00:08:07,440 --> 00:08:11,760
That confirms buyers are defending that area
again.

109
00:08:11,760 --> 00:08:18,080
Without that validation from volume swings,
it's risky to bet on the breakout continuing.

110
00:08:18,080 --> 00:08:24,610
Reading these volume clues is so helpful for
discerning real strength versus smart money

111
00:08:24,610 --> 00:08:25,610
traps.

112
00:08:25,610 --> 00:08:31,920
The moves need to fit the typical patterns
- break on rising volume, pullback on falling

113
00:08:31,920 --> 00:08:35,750
volume, then rising again at retest.

114
00:08:35,750 --> 00:08:40,540
This is the framework for analyzing potential
breakouts.

115
00:08:40,540 --> 00:08:44,010
Breakouts that start downtrends follow the
same pattern.

116
00:08:44,010 --> 00:08:49,580
It doesn't matter if it's continuing bearish
momentum or reversing from bullish.

117
00:08:49,580 --> 00:08:55,430
The only difference is it breaks below support
instead of above resistance.

118
00:08:55,430 --> 00:09:01,149
But volume should be high on the drop through
the zone to confirm selling pressure breaking

119
00:09:01,149 --> 00:09:02,149
it.

120
00:09:02,149 --> 00:09:07,140
Then, we want a return back up to test that
new area.

121
00:09:07,140 --> 00:09:13,060
And again, falling volume validates buyers
aren't in control here yet.

122
00:09:13,060 --> 00:09:17,710
Most importantly, declining markets need rising
volume too.

123
00:09:17,710 --> 00:09:23,600
As it extends lower, increasing selling volumes
prove real downward strength.

124
00:09:23,600 --> 00:09:30,640
Once the buyers can't keep pace at the retest,
look for volume to spike as the sellers take

125
00:09:30,640 --> 00:09:31,640
control.

126
00:09:31,640 --> 00:09:38,540
Those volume inflections confirm healthy breakdowns
versus fake traps.

127
00:09:38,540 --> 00:09:43,920
When looking to enter a retest trade, it's
not enough for the price to just touch the

128
00:09:43,920 --> 00:09:46,680
old support/resistance zone.

129
00:09:46,680 --> 00:09:49,019
That's barely a retest at all.

130
00:09:49,019 --> 00:09:54,980
You want to see some confirmation that smart
money are genuinely treating it as a new level.

131
00:09:54,980 --> 00:10:01,060
For me, the best way is through candlestick
signals at the zone.

132
00:10:01,060 --> 00:10:07,080
An engulfing candle that swallows up the previous
one shows a reversal underway.

133
00:10:07,080 --> 00:10:12,579
Or a pin bar wick rejection off the area is
a solid sign too.

134
00:10:12,579 --> 00:10:18,380
That's a much stronger indication that the
new level is holding, and it’s not hovering

135
00:10:18,380 --> 00:10:20,510
there without conviction.

136
00:10:20,510 --> 00:10:24,830
Just waiting for a simple touch isn't enough
evidence for me.

137
00:10:24,830 --> 00:10:31,530
But catching those engulfing or pin bar signals
right at the old break point, level ups the

138
00:10:31,530 --> 00:10:37,339
odds the move will continue in my direction
after the retest.

139
00:10:37,339 --> 00:10:42,720
One thing that's helped improve my breakout
retests is taking advantage of patterns on

140
00:10:42,720 --> 00:10:44,780
smaller timeframes.

141
00:10:44,780 --> 00:10:48,730
Like this chart - I mainly trade the H4.

142
00:10:48,730 --> 00:10:55,570
But zooming into a 30min view, I spotted an
engulfing candlestick forming right at the

143
00:10:55,570 --> 00:10:57,790
support zone break point.

144
00:10:57,790 --> 00:11:05,520
Volume was also validating the move with high
volume on the drop and low on the pullback.

145
00:11:05,520 --> 00:11:11,650
So with that bearish engulfing candle plus
volume check, this would have been a pretty

146
00:11:11,650 --> 00:11:13,260
decent trade.

147
00:11:13,260 --> 00:11:18,870
Now for the stop, you have 2 main areas: above
the engulfing candle.

148
00:11:18,870 --> 00:11:23,680
Or you simply set the stop a few points above
the whole resistance zone.

149
00:11:23,680 --> 00:11:29,050
So using patterns on lower timeframes for
entries, but keeping the stop based on the

150
00:11:29,050 --> 00:11:34,769
broader zone, can be a much safer retest strategy.

151
00:11:34,769 --> 00:11:41,029
One of the most reliable signals I see at
retest zones is a big pin bar candle.

152
00:11:41,029 --> 00:11:47,060
It literally screams that buyers or sellers
are stepping up to defend that area.

153
00:11:47,060 --> 00:11:52,730
A pin bar shows up as a small body with a
long upper or lower wick.

154
00:11:52,730 --> 00:11:58,170
This rejection at the retest shows traders
are fighting over that price.

155
00:11:58,170 --> 00:12:03,190
Catching strong pin bars precisely where the
market breaks out of a range gives such a

156
00:12:03,190 --> 00:12:05,230
high-probability entry.

157
00:12:05,230 --> 00:12:08,820
The bigger the pin, the more force was in
that rejection.

158
00:12:08,820 --> 00:12:13,390
Plus, the volume needs to be above average
too.

159
00:12:13,390 --> 00:12:19,279
That confirms heavy volumes swapping hands
as buyers and sellers are battling there.

160
00:12:19,279 --> 00:12:26,560
For me, these obvious pin bars that pop out
at a retest zone are just begging to be traded.

161
00:12:26,560 --> 00:12:32,070
As soon as I see one, I'll enter in with the
expectation the rejection holds and the move

162
00:12:32,070 --> 00:12:33,680
continues.

163
00:12:33,680 --> 00:12:40,680
The combination of pin bars with volume spikes
at a retest point is one of my go-to strategies.

164
00:12:40,680 --> 00:12:47,550
And I know it can be tempting to jump in right
away when a big breakout happens.

165
00:12:47,550 --> 00:12:52,019
But being disciplined and waiting for a retest
is so important.

166
00:12:52,019 --> 00:12:58,460
Even if you miss a few trades that keep running,
that's better than entering early before letting

167
00:12:58,460 --> 00:13:00,900
the market reset itself.

168
00:13:00,900 --> 00:13:03,940
Those premature entries are riskier.

169
00:13:03,940 --> 00:13:10,320
By waiting, you get to see how volume behaves
on the break compared to the pullback.

170
00:13:10,320 --> 00:13:17,240
You can also watch for solid candlestick patterns
showing buyers/sellers stepping up again at

171
00:13:17,240 --> 00:13:19,320
the old level.

172
00:13:19,320 --> 00:13:26,399
Most importantly, it allows weak positions
from nervous traders to get flushed out first.

173
00:13:26,399 --> 00:13:32,740
Then you enter with stronger footing once
the area has reset as support or resistance.

174
00:13:32,740 --> 00:13:36,510
I know it's boring to sit on your hands at
first sometimes.

175
00:13:36,510 --> 00:13:42,589
But patience at retests creates a much firmer
base for the move to continue.

176
00:13:42,589 --> 00:13:48,889
Don't compromise on this rule just because
FOMO bites!

177
00:13:48,889 --> 00:13:54,670
The initial retest after a breakout is often
the most important one for me.

178
00:13:54,670 --> 00:14:00,450
When price first returns to a newly established
support or resistance zone, that sets the

179
00:14:00,450 --> 00:14:03,180
tone for what's likely to follow.

180
00:14:03,180 --> 00:14:08,900
If it holds and bounces back in the direction
of the original move, it confirms that level

181
00:14:08,900 --> 00:14:10,980
is now significant.

182
00:14:10,980 --> 00:14:18,149
But the moment it violates that zone twice,
the likelihood of a new wave decreases a lot.

183
00:14:18,149 --> 00:14:25,329
Traders will be less inclined to defend an
area if it fails as a new boundary once already.

184
00:14:25,329 --> 00:14:27,510
The impact is lessened.

185
00:14:27,510 --> 00:14:34,230
That's why I put extra focus on how the market
interacts with freshly broken levels the first

186
00:14:34,230 --> 00:14:36,940
time it re-encounters them.

187
00:14:36,940 --> 00:14:41,600
That initial test often makes or breaks the
whole pattern.

188
00:14:41,600 --> 00:14:47,880
Often times, a second retest of a breakout
zone usually isn't as strong as the initial

189
00:14:47,880 --> 00:14:48,880
one.

190
00:14:48,880 --> 00:14:50,180
Here’s why.

191
00:14:50,180 --> 00:14:56,180
When price first comes back to that area,
any traders who entered on the initial breakout

192
00:14:56,180 --> 00:14:58,970
would still be in their positions.

193
00:14:58,970 --> 00:15:02,230
But if it tests again after that?

194
00:15:02,230 --> 00:15:04,500
They would've closed out already.

195
00:15:04,500 --> 00:15:11,880
So during a second retest, there's less buy/sell
orders stacked up from the original breakout

196
00:15:11,880 --> 00:15:16,750
traders still chasing gains or protecting
stops.

197
00:15:16,750 --> 00:15:22,370
Smart money already collected those first
retest trades, so they're less motivated to

198
00:15:22,370 --> 00:15:24,230
defend it again.

199
00:15:24,230 --> 00:15:29,680
They're not hunting for as many stops or liquidity
anymore either.

200
00:15:29,680 --> 00:15:35,829
In this chart you can see it clearly - price
bounced perfectly off the zone the first time

201
00:15:35,829 --> 00:15:36,829
back.

202
00:15:36,829 --> 00:15:38,600
But on the second touch?

203
00:15:38,600 --> 00:15:40,920
It cleanly broke through with ease.

204
00:15:40,920 --> 00:15:42,060
Support was weaker.

205
00:15:42,060 --> 00:15:57,690
So for the best odds, focus on trading that
crucial first retest.

